To evaluate the dietary effects of replacement of FM with MW in the diets of red seabream, a feeding trial was conducted. Partial or complete replacement of FM with DMW-1 in the diets of red seabream led to significantly increased FL compared to in fish fed with the 65% FM diets (
 Figure 1; 
 Table 5). The BW gain of fish increased depending on the level of DMW-1 content in the experimental diets (
 Figure 1; 
 Table 5). The feed intake increased with the higher MW inclusion, but there were no clear differences between the feed conversion ratios for any of the dietary groups (
 Table 5). In the 65% MW + MO group, the FL gain did not show any difference, but the BW gain rates, specific growth rates (SGR), and feed intake levels were significantly decreased compared with in the 65% MW group.
